      'Courtesy lane is available for senior citizens, PWDs, pregnant women, and solo parents \u2014 bring supporting documents',
      'Keep a scanned copy of your passport\'s data page on your phone and in cloud storage for emergencies',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DFA Passport Appointment System', url: 'https://www.passport.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DFA Passport Requirements (New Adult)', url: 'https://consular.dfa.gov.ph/adult-new/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DFA Passport FAQ', url: 'https://consular.dfa.gov.ph/passport-faq/'),
    ],
  ),
  'drivers-license': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'drivers-license',
    title: 'Get a Driver\'s License (LTO)',
    description: 'A non-professional driver\'s license lets you legally drive a private vehicle and is a widely accepted government ID.',
    why: 'Required by law to drive. Also one of the most accepted IDs for banking and government transactions. Valid for 5 years.',
    how: 'Step 1: Get a Student Permit at LTO \u2014 bring PSA birth certificate, valid ID, medical certificate, and pass the written exam. Step 2: After holding a student permit, apply for a non-professional license with a practical driving test. Process at lto.gov.ph or any LTO office.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    requirements: [
      'Must be at least 16 years old for Student Permit, 17 years old for Non-Professional License',
      'PSA-issued birth certificate (original and photocopy)',
      'One (1) valid government-issued ID (PhilSys National ID, passport, UMID, TIN card, voter\'s ID)',
      'Medical certificate from an LTO-accredited clinic (physical and drug test)',
      'Completion certificate for the 15-hour Theoretical Driving Course (TDC) from an LTO-accredited driving school',
      'Completion certificate for the Practical Driving Course (PDC) \u2014 required for non-professional license',
      'Student Permit held for at least 30 days (to apply for non-professional license)',
      'No unsettled traffic violations',
    ],
    steps: [
      'PHASE 1: STUDENT PERMIT',
      'Step 1: Get a medical certificate from an LTO-accredited medical clinic (usually located near LTO offices). Cost: \u20B1350-\u20B1500',
      'Step 2: Complete the 15-hour Theoretical Driving Course (TDC) at an LTO-accredited driving school. You\'ll receive a TDC completion certificate',
      'Step 3: Visit your nearest LTO District/Licensing Office and get an Application for Permits and Licenses (APL) form',
      'Step 4: Fill out the APL form and submit with your requirements at the evaluation counter',
      'Step 5: Pay the student permit fee (approximately \u20B1317.63 \u2014 includes application, computer, and permit fees)',
      'Step 6: Have your photo and biometrics captured',
      'Step 7: Take the theoretical (written) exam \u2014 you must pass to receive your Student Permit',
      'Step 8: Receive your Student Permit (valid for 1 year)',
      'PHASE 2: NON-PROFESSIONAL LICENSE (after 30+ days with Student Permit)',
      'Step 9: Complete the Practical Driving Course (PDC) at an LTO-accredited driving school',
      'Step 10: Return to an LTO office with your Student Permit, PDC completion certificate, and other requirements',
      'Step 11: Fill out a new APL form for Non-Professional License',
      'Step 12: Take the practical driving test at the LTO office',
      'Step 13: If you pass, pay the license fee (approximately \u20B1585 + \u20B167.63 computer fee)',
      'Step 14: Have your photo and biometrics captured for the license card',
      'Step 15: Receive your Non-Professional Driver\'s License',
    ],
    fees: 'Student Permit: ~\u20B1317.63 (application + computer + permit fees). Non-Professional License: ~\u20B1652.63 (license + computer fees). Medical certificate: \u20B1350-\u20B1500. TDC: \u20B12,000-\u20B14,000. PDC: \u20B13,000-\u20B18,000. Total estimated cost: \u20B16,000-\u20B113,000+',
    processingTime: 'Student Permit: same day (if you pass the exam). Non-Professional License: same day (if you pass the driving test). Minimum 30 days must pass between getting Student Permit and applying for license',
    tips: [
      'Complete TDC and medical exam BEFORE visiting LTO \u2014 you cannot apply without these',
      'Schedule your LTO visit early in the morning (offices open at 8AM) to avoid long queues',
      'Some LTO offices have online appointment systems \u2014 check lto.gov.ph for availability',
      'Study for the theoretical exam using the LTO Reviewer app or practice exams online',
      'The practical driving test includes starting on an incline, parallel parking, and navigating an obstacle course',
      'Your non-professional license is valid for 5 years, with potential 10-year validity if you maintain a clean driving record',
      'You CANNOT drive alone with just a Student Permit \u2014 a licensed driver must accompany you at all times',
      'Keep your medical certificate fresh \u2014 it\'s only valid for 30 days from issuance for LTO purposes',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'LTO Official Website', url: 'https://lto.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'LTO Driver\'s License Guide', url: 'https://ltoportal.org/drivers-license/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'LTO Student Permit Requirements', url: 'https://ltoportal.org/lto-student-permit/'),
    ],
  ),
  'voters-id': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'voters-id',
    title: 'Register as a Voter (COMELEC)',
    description: 'Voter registration gives you the right to vote in national and local elections \u2014 and your voter\'s certificate is accepted as a valid ID.',
    why: 'Voting is your civic duty and your voice in shaping the Philippines. Local elections directly affect your community, schools, roads, and health services. Registration is free.',
    how: 'Register at the COMELEC office in your municipality/city. Bring a valid ID and proof of residency. Online pre-registration is available at voterregistration.comelec.gov.ph. Registration periods open before every election.',
    priority: 'important',
    requirements: [
      'Must be at least 18 years old on or before election day',
      'Must have resided in the Philippines for at least one (1) year and in the city/municipality where you intend to register for at least six (6) months before the election',
      'One (1) valid government-issued ID with photo (PhilSys National ID, SSS/GSIS/UMID, passport, driver\'s license, PRC ID, postal ID)',
      'Note: Cedulas (Community Tax Certificates), PNP clearance, and employee IDs are NOT accepted',
      'If no valid ID: a registered voter from your precinct or a relative within the 4th civil degree can identify you under oath',
      'Must not be disqualified from voting by law (e.g., convicted of a crime involving disloyalty to the government, insanity)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Check if voter registration is currently open \u2014 COMELEC opens registration periods before elections (check comelec.gov.ph for schedules)',
      'Step 2: Download the CEF-1 (Application for Registration) form from comelec.gov.ph, or get one at the Office of the Election Officer (OEO) in your city/municipality',
      'Step 3: Fill out the form completely \u2014 use black ink and print legibly. Include your full name, address, birthdate, and other personal details',
      'Step 4: Visit the OEO (COMELEC office) in the city/municipality where you intend to vote',
      'Step 5: Submit your accomplished CEF-1 form and present your valid ID',
      'Step 6: Have your biometrics captured \u2014 photo, fingerprints, and signature',
      'Step 7: Your application will be reviewed and included in the list of voters for your precinct',
      'Step 8: Check the COMELEC website or visit the OEO to confirm your registration was approved and to find your precinct assignment',
      'Step 9: On election day, bring your voter\'s ID or any valid ID to your assigned precinct to vote',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 voter registration has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Registration: same day (biometrics and application submission). Approval and precinct assignment: processed during the registration period. Voter\'s ID/certification: varies',
    tips: [
      'Registration periods are limited \u2014 don\'t wait until the last day. COMELEC typically opens registration 1-2 years before a national election',
      'If you\'ve moved to a new city/municipality, you need to transfer your registration \u2014 file a transfer application at the OEO of your new residence',
      'You can check your voter registration status online at comelec.gov.ph using the Precinct Finder',
      'The Voter\'s ID is a valid government-issued ID accepted for many transactions',
      'Deactivated voters (those who failed to vote in two consecutive elections) must re-register',
      'Arrive early at the OEO \u2014 registration centers can get very crowded, especially near deadline dates',
      'Overseas Filipinos can register for overseas absentee voting at Philippine embassies or consulates',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'COMELEC Official Website', url: 'https://comelec.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'COMELEC Registration Requirements', url: 'https://comelec.gov.ph/?r=VoterRegistration/WhatisVoterRegistration/RegistrationRequirements'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'COMELEC How to Register', url: 'https://comelec.gov.ph/?r=VoterRegistration/HowtoRegister'),
    ],
  ),
  'first-time-jobseeker': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'first-time-jobseeker',
    title: 'Get your First Time Jobseeker Certificate',
    description: 'A barangay certificate that exempts first-time job seekers from paying fees for government documents needed for employment.',
    why: 'Republic Act 11261 (First Time Jobseekers Assistance Act) exempts you from paying documentary requirements for your first employment \u2014 including NBI clearance, police clearance, barangay clearance, and others. This saves you \u20B1500\u2013\u20B11,500 in fees.',
    how: 'Visit your Barangay Hall and request a First Time Jobseeker Certificate. Bring a valid ID and fill out the application form. The certificate is valid for 1 year from issuance.',
    priority: 'critical',
    requirements: [
      'Any valid ID (school ID, birth certificate, voter\'s ID, or barangay ID)',
      'Filled-out oath of undertaking (provided at the barangay hall)',
      'Must be a resident of the barangay where you\'re applying',
      'Must be 18 years old and above',
      'Must not have been previously employed (this is for first-time job seekers only)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Go to your Barangay Hall during office hours (usually 8 AM \u2013 5 PM, Monday to Friday)',
      'Ask for the First Time Jobseeker Certificate application at the barangay secretary\'s office',
      'Fill out the application form and the Oath of Undertaking \u2014 this is your sworn statement that you\'re a first-time jobseeker',
      'Submit the form with a photocopy of your valid ID',
      'Wait for processing \u2014 usually takes 15-30 minutes',
      'Receive your certificate. Keep the original and make 3-4 photocopies',
      'Use the certificate when applying for: NBI Clearance (free), Police Clearance (free), Barangay Clearance (free), PSA Birth Certificate (free), and other employment requirements',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 the certificate itself is free. It also exempts you from fees on other documents',
    processingTime: 'Same day \u2014 usually 15-30 minutes',
    tips: [
      'Get this BEFORE applying for NBI clearance, police clearance, or any other employment documents \u2014 it exempts you from their fees',
      'The certificate is valid for 1 year. If you don\'t find a job within that period, you can renew it',
      'Make multiple photocopies \u2014 you\'ll need to present it at each government office where you claim exemption',
      'Some barangays may ask you to return the next day for signing by the barangay captain. Call ahead to check',
      'This only applies to your FIRST employment. Freelance work or online jobs may or may not count depending on the barangay\'s interpretation',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'RA 11261 Full Text (First Time Jobseekers Act)', url: 'https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2019/04/10/republic-act-no-11261/'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 2: Banking & Emergency Fund ──────────────────────────────────────
  'savings-account': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'savings-account',
    title: 'Open a bank savings account',
    description: 'A traditional savings account at BDO, BPI, Metrobank, or UnionBank gives you access to ATMs nationwide, checks, and formal banking services.',
    why: 'Cash under a mattress earns nothing and can be stolen. A savings account is the baseline for receiving payroll, paying bills, and accessing the financial system. Required for most loan applications.',
    how: 'Visit any branch with two valid IDs and an initial deposit (BPI: \u20B13,000; BDO: \u20B12,000; UnionBank: \u20B10). UnionBank\'s EON account and BDO\'s account can be opened fully online. Choose a bank near your home or office.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/accounts',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track in Accounts',
    requirements: [
      'Two (2) valid government-issued IDs with photo (passport, driver\'s license, UMID, PhilSys National ID, PRC ID, voter\'s ID, postal ID)',
      'TIN (Tax Identification Number) \u2014 required by most banks even if unemployed',
      'Proof of billing address: latest utility bill (electricity, water, internet, phone) or credit card statement \u2014 must show your name and address',
      'Initial deposit amount (varies by bank: BPI \u20B13,000, BDO \u20B12,000, Metrobank \u20B12,000, UnionBank \u20B10 for EON, Security Bank \u20B15,000-\u20B110,000)',
      'Active mobile number and email address',
      'For online account opening: smartphone with camera for selfie verification',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Choose a bank based on branch proximity, ATM network, minimum balance requirements, and fees. Top choices for first-timers: BPI, BDO, UnionBank, or Metrobank',
      'Step 2 (In-Branch): Visit the nearest branch during banking hours (typically 9AM-3PM weekdays)',
      'Step 3: Get a queue number for \'New Accounts\' and wait for your turn',
      'Step 4: Fill out the multi-page application form (Customer Information Sheet) \u2014 provide personal info, employment details, source of funds, and TIN',
      'Step 5: Submit the form with your two valid IDs. The bank officer will verify and photocopy your documents',
      'Step 6: The bank may ask clarifying questions about your employment, income source, and purpose of the account',
      'Step 7: Make your initial deposit at the cashier',
      'Step 8: Receive your passbook and/or ATM card (some banks issue ATM cards immediately, others mail them within 5-7 days)',
      'Step 9: Activate your online/mobile banking by downloading the bank\'s app and registering your account',
      'Alternative (Online): Banks like UnionBank (EON), BPI, and BDO allow fully online account opening \u2014 download the app, scan your ID, take a selfie, and fund via InstaPay',
    ],
    fees: 'Account opening: Free. Maintaining balance varies (BPI: \u20B13,000, BDO: \u20B12,000, Metrobank: \u20B110,000). Below-minimum balance fee: \u20B1300/month. ATM card replacement: \u20B1150-\u20B1350. Some accounts have zero maintaining balance (e.g., UnionBank EON, BPI Save-Up)',
    processingTime: 'In-branch: 30-60 minutes (same day). Online account opening: 5-15 minutes (may take 1-2 business days for full verification)',
    tips: [
      'Choose a bank with many ATMs near your home and office to avoid withdrawal fees (\u20B118-\u20B125 per transaction at other bank ATMs)',
      'UnionBank EON is excellent as a first account \u2014 zero maintaining balance, free online transfers, and fully online opening',
      'Always set up online/mobile banking immediately \u2014 it saves you from branch visits for transfers and bill payments',
      'Keep your maintaining balance above the minimum to avoid the \u20B1300/month penalty fee',
      'Set up your payroll to deposit directly into your bank account \u2014 ask HR for the bank enrollment form',
      'PDIC (Philippine Deposit Insurance Corporation) insures deposits up to \u20B1500,000 per depositor per bank',
      'Compare interest rates \u2014 most traditional banks offer only 0.10-0.25% p.a. on regular savings',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BPI Account Opening Requirements', url: 'https://www.bpi.com.ph/personal/bank/list-of-account-opening-requirements'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BDO Personal Accounts', url: 'https://www.bdo.com.ph/personal'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Security Bank Documents Needed', url: 'https://www.securitybank.com/blog/documents-you-need-to-open-a-bank-account-in-the-philippines/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PDIC Deposit Insurance', url: 'https://www.pdic.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  'digital-savings': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'digital-savings',
    title: 'Open a high-yield digital savings account',
    description: 'ING (4% p.a.), CIMB (4.5% p.a.), and Maya (3.5% p.a.) offer savings rates far above traditional banks, with no maintaining balance.',
    why: 'Traditional banks pay 0.10\u20130.25% interest. Digital banks pay 3\u20135%. On \u20B150,000 in emergency funds, that\'s the difference between \u20B1125/year vs. \u20B12,000/year \u2014 with zero maintaining balance.',
    how: 'Download the app: ING Philippines, CIMB Bank, Maya, or Tonik. Sign up with a selfie + valid ID (passport or PhilSys). Account opens in minutes. Transfer money via InstaPay (\u20B150 fee, unless free with your sending bank).',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/accounts',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track in Accounts',
    requirements: [
      'A smartphone (Android or iOS) with internet connection',
      'One (1) valid government-issued ID (PhilSys National ID, passport, driver\'s license, UMID, PRC ID, voter\'s ID, postal ID)',
      'Active mobile number (for OTP verification)',
      'Active email address',
      'Selfie for identity verification (taken in-app during registration)',
      'No minimum deposit required for most digital banks',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Choose a digital bank based on interest rates and features. Top options: Maya Bank (up to 8% p.a. on Personal Goals), Tonik (up to 6% p.a. on time deposits), GoTyme (up to 5% p.a.), GCash/CIMB GSave (up to 4% p.a.)',
      'Step 2: Download the digital bank\'s app from Google Play Store or Apple App Store',
      'Step 3: Open the app and tap \'Sign Up\' or \'Create Account\'',
      'Step 4: Enter your mobile number and verify via OTP (one-time password)',
      'Step 5: Fill out personal details \u2014 full name, birthdate, address, email, source of funds',
      'Step 6: Upload or scan your valid government ID using your phone\'s camera',
      'Step 7: Take a selfie for identity verification \u2014 follow in-app instructions for proper lighting and angle',
      'Step 8: Review and submit your application',
      'Step 9: Wait for verification \u2014 most digital banks approve within minutes, some may take up to 24 hours',
      'Step 10: Once approved, you can start depositing via InstaPay, PESONet, or fund transfer from your existing bank account',
      'For GCash GSave: Open GCash app > tap \'Save Money\' > GSave > \'Open a GSave Account\' > follow prompts to create CIMB savings account within GCash',
    ],
    fees: 'No account opening fee. No maintaining balance. No closing fee. Fund transfers via InstaPay: Free or \u20B125-\u20B150 depending on the sending bank/app',
    processingTime: 'Account opening: 5-15 minutes. Verification: instant to 24 hours. Account fully usable immediately upon approval',
    tips: [
      'Digital banks are regulated by the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) and deposits are insured by PDIC up to \u20B11,000,000 per depositor per bank \u2014 your money is safe',
      'Use digital bank accounts for your emergency fund \u2014 higher interest rates mean your money grows faster',
      'Maya Bank\'s Personal Goals feature lets you create up to 5 sub-accounts for different savings goals (e.g., emergency fund, travel, gadget)',
      'Interest rates change frequently \u2014 check the latest rates before opening. Promotional rates may be temporary',
      'You can link most digital bank accounts to e-wallets (GCash, Maya) for easy transfers',
      'Don\'t put all your money in one digital bank \u2014 spread across 2-3 to maximize PDIC insurance coverage and take advantage of different promo rates',
      'Set up auto-transfer from your payroll bank to your digital savings \u2014 automate the habit of saving',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Maya Bank Savings', url: 'https://www.mayabank.ph/savings/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Tonik Digital Bank', url: 'https://tonik.com/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'GoTyme Bank', url: 'https://www.gotyme.com.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BSP List of Digital Banks', url: 'https://www.bsp.gov.ph/Pages/InclusiveFinance/DigitalBanks.aspx'),
    ],
  ),
  'emergency-fund-3mo': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'emergency-fund-3mo',
    title: 'Save 3 months of living expenses',
    description: 'Your emergency fund covers job loss, medical emergencies, car repairs, or any unexpected expense \u2014 without going into debt.',
    why: 'Without an emergency fund, any unexpected expense forces you to borrow (credit card, 5-6 loan). The average Filipino salary takes 3\u20136 months to find a new job. Your emergency fund is your self-insurance.',
    how: 'Calculate your monthly expenses (rent + food + transport + utilities + insurance). Multiply by 3. Keep this in a separate high-yield savings account \u2014 don\'t mix it with your spending money. Automate a monthly transfer.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/goals',
    appLinkLabel: 'Set Goal',
    requirements: [
      'A clear list of your essential monthly expenses (rent, food, transportation, utilities, insurance premiums, loan payments)',
      'A separate savings account dedicated ONLY to your emergency fund (preferably a high-yield digital bank)',
      'A commitment to consistent monthly savings \u2014 even small amounts count',
      'Knowledge of your monthly take-home pay (net salary after deductions)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: List all your essential monthly expenses \u2014 rent/housing, food/groceries, transportation, utilities (electricity, water, internet, phone), insurance premiums, loan payments, and any other non-negotiable costs',
      'Step 2: Add them up to get your total monthly essential expenses. Example: \u20B18,000 rent + \u20B16,000 food + \u20B13,000 transport + \u20B12,000 utilities + \u20B11,000 insurance = \u20B120,000/month',
      'Step 3: Multiply by 3 to get your 3-month emergency fund target. Example: \u20B120,000 x 3 = \u20B160,000',
      'Step 4: Open a separate high-yield digital savings account (Maya, Tonik, GoTyme) exclusively for your emergency fund \u2014 do NOT mix it with your spending money',
      'Step 5: Determine how much you can save per month. Use the 50-30-20 rule: 50% needs, 30% savings, 20% wants. If that\'s too aggressive, start with 10-20% of your income',
      'Step 6: Break down your target into monthly chunks. Example: \u20B160,000 target \u00F7 12 months = \u20B15,000/month. If that\'s too much, extend the timeline \u2014 even \u20B12,000/month gets you there in 30 months',
      'Step 7: Automate your savings \u2014 set up an auto-transfer from your payroll bank to your emergency fund account on payday',
      'Step 8: Track your progress monthly. Celebrate milestones (\u20B110,000, \u20B130,000, goal reached!)',
      'Step 9: Once you reach 3 months, keep going to 6 months for full financial security',
      'Step 10: If you ever use your emergency fund, prioritize replenishing it immediately',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 no fees to save money. High-yield digital bank accounts have no maintaining balance or account fees',
    processingTime: 'Depends on your income and savings rate. At \u20B15,000/month savings: ~12 months for a \u20B160,000 target. At \u20B12,000/month: ~30 months. Start today regardless of the amount',
    tips: [
      'Start with whatever you can \u2014 even \u20B150 or \u20B1100 a day adds up to \u20B11,500-\u20B13,000 a month',
      'The emergency fund is NOT for wants \u2014 it\'s strictly for genuine emergencies: job loss, medical bills, car breakdown, home repairs',
      'Keep it in a liquid, accessible account \u2014 NOT in time deposits, stocks, or investments you can\'t withdraw instantly',
      'In the Filipino context, family obligations are real. Budget for them, but don\'t let them derail your emergency fund completely',
      'Cut unnecessary expenses to boost savings: cook at home instead of food delivery, cancel unused subscriptions, carpool instead of ride-hailing apps',
      'Use the \'pay yourself first\' method \u2014 transfer savings BEFORE you start spending, not after',
      'Don\'t be discouraged by slow progress \u2014 a partial emergency fund is infinitely better than none',
      'Consider the ipon (saving) challenge: save \u20B150 on week 1, \u20B1100 on week 2, \u20B1150 on week 3, etc. By week 52, you\'ll have over \u20B168,000',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'How to Build an Emergency Fund (MoneyMax)', url: 'https://www.moneymax.ph/personal-finance/articles/start-emergency-fund'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Emergency Fund Guide for Filipinos (Maya)', url: 'https://www.maya.ph/stories/5-best-practices-for-building-an-emergency-fund-a-guide-for-filipinos'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Emergency Fund Philippines (FinMerkado)', url: 'https://www.finmerkado.ph/post/emergency-fund-philippines-high-interest-savings'),
    ],
  ),
  'understand-payslip': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'understand-payslip',
    title: 'Understand your payslip deductions',
    description: 'Know exactly what SSS, PhilHealth, Pag-IBIG, and withholding tax amounts are being deducted from your salary every month.',
    why: 'Many Filipinos don\'t know what they\'re actually earning vs. what\'s being withheld. Understanding deductions lets you verify your contributions are correct and plan your net take-home budget accurately.',
    how: 'Check your payslip monthly. Verify SSS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG amounts match the official tables. Withholding tax depends on your salary bracket. Use Sandalan\'s Contribution Calculator to verify your employer is computing correctly.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Calculate Deductions',
    requirements: [
      'Your latest payslip (printed or digital \u2014 ask HR if you don\'t receive one regularly)',
      'Access to the SSS contribution table (2025: 15% total contribution rate, employee share varies by salary bracket)',
      'Access to the PhilHealth premium table (2025: 5% of monthly basic salary, split equally between employer and employee)',
      'Knowledge of Pag-IBIG contribution rates (2% of monthly salary, max \u20B1200/month for employee)',
      'BIR Withholding Tax Table (TRAIN Law graduated rates)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Get your payslip \u2014 request it from HR/payroll if you don\'t automatically receive one. You have a legal right to a payslip under DOLE regulations',
      'Step 2: Identify your Gross Salary \u2014 this is your total salary before any deductions',
      'Step 3: Check SSS deduction \u2014 for 2025, the total contribution rate is 15% (employee share varies). Use the SSS contribution table to verify your deduction matches your Monthly Salary Credit (MSC). MSC ranges from \u20B15,000 to \u20B135,000',
      'Step 4: Check PhilHealth deduction \u2014 the premium rate is 5% of your monthly basic salary, split 50/50 with your employer. Your share is 2.5%. Minimum: \u20B1250/month (your share). Maximum: \u20B12,500/month (for salaries \u20B1100,000+)',
      'Step 5: Check Pag-IBIG deduction \u2014 your employee share is 2% of monthly salary (max compensation basis is \u20B110,000, so max deduction is \u20B1200/month). Your employer matches this amount',
      'Step 6: Check Withholding Tax \u2014 subtract SSS + PhilHealth + Pag-IBIG from your gross salary to get taxable income. Under the TRAIN Law: income up to \u20B120,833/month (\u20B1250,000/year) is tax-exempt. Above that, graduated rates apply (20-35%)',
      'Step 7: Verify Net Pay \u2014 Gross Salary minus (SSS + PhilHealth + Pag-IBIG + Withholding Tax + any voluntary deductions like loans) = your take-home pay',
      'Step 8: Compare your computed amounts with what\'s on your payslip. If there are discrepancies, bring it up with HR/payroll immediately',
      'Step 9: Check your SSS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG portals to confirm your employer is actually remitting the deducted amounts',
    ],
    fees: 'N/A \u2014 these are mandatory deductions, not fees. Your total mandatory deductions typically range from 8-15% of your gross salary depending on your bracket',
    processingTime: 'N/A \u2014 payslip review should be done every payday (semi-monthly or monthly)',
    tips: [
      'Your employer is LEGALLY REQUIRED to give you a payslip. If they refuse, report it to DOLE',
      'Use online calculators like taxcalculatorphilippines.com or sweldongpinoy.com to double-check your deductions',
      'Under the TRAIN Law (2018), if you earn \u20B1250,000 or below annually (about \u20B120,833/month), you are EXEMPT from income tax',
      'Overtime pay, holiday pay, night shift differential, and hazard pay are computed separately and have different tax treatments',
      '13th month pay and other benefits up to \u20B190,000 combined are tax-exempt',
      'If your employer deducts contributions but doesn\'t remit them to SSS/PhilHealth/Pag-IBIG, this is illegal. Check your contribution portals regularly',
      'Keep all your payslips \u2014 they serve as proof of income for loan applications, credit cards, and future employment',
      'Your BIR Form 2316 (issued every January) summarizes your annual income and taxes \u2014 cross-reference it with your total payslip deductions for the year',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS 2025 Contribution Table', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/contribution/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Premium Contributions', url: 'https://www.philhealth.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Pag-IBIG Contribution Table', url: 'https://www.pagibigfund.gov.ph/Membership.html'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BIR Withholding Tax Table (TRAIN Law)', url: 'https://www.bir.gov.ph/tax-information/withholding-tax'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Sweldong Pinoy Tax Calculator', url: 'https://www.sweldongpinoy.com/'),
    ],
  ),
  'credit-card': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'credit-card',
    title: 'Get a credit card (responsibly)',
    description: 'A credit card builds your credit history, earns rewards/cashback, and provides a safety net \u2014 only if you pay the full balance every month.',
    why: 'Credit cards are a tool, not free money. Paying in full every month costs you nothing (0% effective rate) and earns rewards. Minimum payments trap you in 24\u201336% annual interest \u2014 the single worst financial mistake Filipinos make.',
    how: 'Apply at BPI (Amore), BDO (Visa Classic), or Security Bank (Complete Cashback). Requirements: Certificate of Employment, 2 months payslips, TIN, and 1 valid ID. Start with a low limit. Golden rule: never charge what you can\'t pay by billing date.',
    priority: 'good-to-have',
    requirements: [
      'Must be 21-65 years old (some banks accept 18+ with a co-signer)',
      'Filipino citizen or foreign national residing in the Philippines for at least 2 years',
      'Minimum gross annual income of \u20B1120,000-\u20B1252,000 (varies by bank and card type \u2014 some starter cards accept lower income)',
      'At least 1 year of regular employment or 1-2 years of profitable business/freelance work',
      'Two (2) valid government-issued IDs with photo (passport, driver\'s license, UMID, PhilSys National ID)',
      'TIN (Tax Identification Number)',
      'Certificate of Employment (COE) with compensation \u2014 request from HR',
      'Latest 2-3 months payslips or ITR (Income Tax Return) for self-employed',
      'Proof of billing address (latest utility bill or credit card statement)',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Check if you meet the minimum income requirement \u2014 most basic cards require \u20B1120,000-\u20B1180,000 gross annual income (\u20B110,000-\u20B115,000/month)',
      'Step 2: Research starter-friendly credit cards. Top picks for first-timers: PNB Ze-Lo Mastercard (no annual fee, low income requirement), BPI Amore Cashback, RCBC Classic Mastercard, Security Bank Complete Cashback',
      'Step 3: Apply online through the bank\'s website (most convenient) or visit a branch. Online applications: go to the bank\'s official website and look for \'Apply for Credit Card\'',
      'Step 4: Fill out the application form \u2014 provide personal details, employment info, income, and existing bank accounts',
      'Step 5: Upload or submit required documents: valid IDs, COE with salary, latest payslips, proof of billing address',
      'Step 6: Wait for the bank\'s evaluation and credit check (they may call your employer or references to verify)',
      'Step 7: If approved, your credit card will be delivered to your billing address within 7-14 business days',
      'Step 8: Activate your card by calling the activation hotline or through the bank\'s mobile app',
      'Step 9: Set up your online banking to monitor transactions and pay your balance',
      'Step 10: Start with small purchases and ALWAYS pay the full balance before the due date',
    ],
    fees: 'Annual fee: \u20B10-\u20B12,500 depending on the card (some starter cards have no annual fee or waive it for the first year). Late payment fee: \u20B1500-\u20B1850. Interest rate on unpaid balance: 2-3.5% per month (24-42% per year). Over-limit fee: \u20B1500. Cash advance fee: \u20B1200-\u20B1500 + interest from day 1',
    processingTime: 'Application evaluation: 7-14 business days. Card delivery (if approved): 5-10 business days after approval. Total: about 2-4 weeks from application to card in hand',
    tips: [
      'GOLDEN RULE: Pay your FULL balance every month by the due date \u2014 this means you pay ZERO interest. Only paying the minimum traps you in 24-42% annual interest',
      'Start with a low credit limit (\u20B110,000-\u20B130,000) until you develop discipline',
      'Use your credit card for regular expenses you\'d buy anyway (groceries, gas, bills) to earn rewards \u2014 then pay it off in full',
      'NEVER use credit card cash advance \u2014 it charges interest from day 1 with no grace period, plus a transaction fee',
      'Set up auto-pay for the full statement balance to never miss a due date',
      'Keep your credit utilization below 30% of your limit (e.g., don\'t charge more than \u20B19,000 on a \u20B130,000 limit)',
      'If you\'re denied, try secured credit cards (backed by a bank deposit) as a stepping stone \u2014 RCBC and BPI offer these',
      'Having an existing savings/checking account with a bank significantly increases your approval chances for their credit card',
      'Never share your credit card number, CVV, or OTP with anyone \u2014 banks will NEVER ask for these via call, text, or email',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'MoneyMax Credit Cards for First-Timers', url: 'https://www.moneymax.ph/credit-card/articles/credit-cards-for-first-timers'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'How to Apply for Your First Credit Card (MoneyMax)', url: 'https://www.moneymax.ph/credit-card/articles/first-credit-card-guide'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'BSP Consumer Protection', url: 'https://www.bsp.gov.ph/Pages/ConsumerProtection/ConsumerProtection.aspx'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 3: Government Contributions ──────────────────────────────────────
  'sss-active': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'sss-active',
    title: 'Verify your SSS contributions are current',
    description: 'Check your SSS contribution history to make sure your employer is remitting your deductions and that your records are accurate.',
    why: 'Some employers deduct SSS but fail to remit \u2014 leaving you with gaps in your contribution history that affect your loan eligibility and eventual pension. You are entitled to sue your employer for this.',
    how: 'Log in to my.sss.gov.ph \u2192 Contributions. Verify each month shows up. If a month is missing and you were employed, file a complaint with SSS. Keep payslip records as proof of your deductions.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Contributions',
    requirements: [
      'Your SSS number (SS number)',
      'A registered My.SSS account at member.sss.gov.ph (if you don\'t have one, register first)',
      'Your My.SSS login credentials (user ID and password)',
      'A computer, tablet, or smartphone with internet access',
      'Your payslips as reference to cross-check deductions vs. actual remittances',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Go to member.sss.gov.ph and log in with your My.SSS user ID and password',
      'Step 2: On the dashboard, hover over or click \'E-Services\' in the menu bar',
      'Step 3: In the dropdown menu, select \'Inquiry\' then \'Contributions\'',
      'Step 4: Your contribution history will display \u2014 it shows each month\'s contribution amount, the employer who remitted, and the posting date',
      'Step 5: Cross-reference with your payslips \u2014 for every month you were employed and had SSS deductions, there should be a corresponding entry',
      'Step 6: If a month is MISSING, it means your employer deducted but did not remit \u2014 this is illegal',
      'Step 7: To check employment history: go to E-Services > Inquiry > Employment History to see all employers who reported you',
      'Step 8: If you find discrepancies, file a formal complaint with SSS \u2014 bring your payslips as evidence',
      'Alternative: Download the SSS Mobile App (available on Google Play and App Store) and log in with your My.SSS credentials to check on the go',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 checking contributions online has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Instant \u2014 contribution records are available immediately upon login. Note: new contributions may take 3-5 working days to post after payment/remittance',
    tips: [
      'Check your contributions at least quarterly \u2014 don\'t wait until you need to file a claim to find out your employer hasn\'t been remitting',
      'Contributions may take 3-5 working days to appear after your employer remits, so don\'t panic if the latest month isn\'t showing yet',
      'Screenshot or download your contribution records periodically as backup documentation',
      'If your employer is not remitting, file a complaint at the nearest SSS branch \u2014 employers who don\'t remit face criminal penalties under RA 11199 (Social Security Act of 2018)',
      'Voluntary members: you can check if your personal payments were posted correctly using the same process',
      'Your total contributions determine your loan eligibility (salary loan requires 36 monthly contributions) and eventual pension amount',
      'If you forgot your My.SSS password, use the \'Forgot Password\' feature \u2014 you\'ll need your SS number and registered email',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'My.SSS Member Portal', url: 'https://member.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Mobile App', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/download-the-sss-mobile-app-2/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Official Website', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'SSS Hotline', url: 'https://www.sss.gov.ph/contact-us/'),
    ],
  ),
  'philhealth-active': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'philhealth-active',
    title: 'Verify your PhilHealth contributions are current',
    description: 'Check that your employer is remitting your PhilHealth contributions and that your membership is active for hospitalization benefits.',
    why: 'If contributions aren\'t posted, you won\'t be able to use PhilHealth benefits when hospitalized. Members without active contributions may need to pay a differential fee to avail coverage.',
    how: 'Log in to PhilHealth member portal at philhealth.gov.ph \u2192 Contributions. Check for gaps. Your employer should give you an MDR (Member Data Record) confirming active status. For outpatient: present PhilHealth ID and MDR at accredited facilities.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Contributions',
    requirements: [
      'Your PhilHealth Identification Number (PIN)',
      'A registered PhilHealth Member Portal account at memberinquiry.philhealth.gov.ph',
      'Login credentials (PhilHealth number and password)',
      'A computer, tablet, or smartphone with internet access',
      'Your payslips for cross-referencing employer deductions',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Go to memberinquiry.philhealth.gov.ph and log in with your PhilHealth number and password',
      'Step 2: If you don\'t have an account yet, click \'Register\' and follow the prompts using your PIN, personal details, and valid email',
      'Step 3: Once logged in, navigate to the Contributions section to view your posted contribution history',
      'Step 4: Verify that each month shows a contribution \u2014 especially if you were employed during that period',
      'Step 5: Check your membership status \u2014 it should show \'Active\' for you to be eligible for hospitalization benefits',
      'Step 6: Cross-reference contributions with your payslip deductions to ensure your employer is remitting correctly',
      'Step 7: If contributions are missing, request your MDR (Member Data Record) from your employer or from a PhilHealth LHIO office',
      'Step 8: Report any discrepancies to PhilHealth by visiting the nearest LHIO or emailing actioncenter@philhealth.gov.ph',
      'Alternative: Email actioncenter@philhealth.gov.ph with your complete name, birthdate, and a photo of your valid ID to request a membership status check',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 checking PhilHealth status online has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Instant \u2014 records are available upon login. New contributions may take several weeks to post after employer remittance',
    tips: [
      'PhilHealth contributions take longer to post compared to SSS \u2014 don\'t panic if the latest months aren\'t showing yet, but do follow up if it\'s been more than 2 months',
      'Your employer is required to issue your MDR (Member Data Record) \u2014 this is your proof of active membership for hospital admissions',
      'Under the Universal Health Care (UHC) Law, all Filipinos are eligible for PhilHealth benefits, but having active contribution status ensures full benefit coverage',
      'Always present your PhilHealth ID or PhilSys National ID (linked to PhilHealth) at hospital admission \u2014 this triggers the automatic deduction of PhilHealth coverage from your bill',
      'If you\'re changing employers, ensure there\'s no gap in contributions \u2014 the new employer should start remitting immediately',
      'Voluntary members (freelancers, self-employed): you can pay contributions at any accredited payment center or through online banking',
      'Keep your Member Data Record (MDR) accessible \u2014 hospitals require this alongside your PhilHealth ID for benefit claims',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Member Portal', url: 'https://memberinquiry.philhealth.gov.ph/member/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Official Website', url: 'https://www.philhealth.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Online Services', url: 'https://www.philhealth.gov.ph/services/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'PhilHealth Action Center Email', url: 'mailto:actioncenter@philhealth.gov.ph'),
    ],
  ),
  'pagibig-active': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'pagibig-active',
    title: 'Verify your Pag-IBIG contributions are current',
    description: 'Confirm monthly Pag-IBIG deductions are being remitted so your housing loan eligibility and MP2 savings are properly building.',
    why: '24 months of Pag-IBIG contributions makes you eligible for housing loans. If your employer isn\'t remitting, you lose eligibility and your contributions may not count.',
    how: 'Log in at pagibig-fund.gov.ph \u2192 Virtual Pag-IBIG \u2192 Member\'s Contribution History. Or text PAG-IBIG <MID number> to 4643. Contact your HR if months are missing.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/contributions',
    appLinkLabel: 'Track Contributions',
    requirements: [
      'Your Pag-IBIG MID (Membership ID) number',
      'A registered Virtual Pag-IBIG account at pagibigfundservices.com/virtualpagibig',
      'Login credentials (registered email and password)',
      'A computer, tablet, or smartphone with internet access',
      'Your payslips for cross-referencing employer deductions',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Go to pagibigfundservices.com/virtualpagibig and log in with your registered email and password',
      'Step 2: If you don\'t have an account, click \'Create Account\' and register using your MID number, personal details, and email address',
      'Step 3: Once logged in, click the MENU icon (upper left on desktop, upper right on mobile)',
      'Step 4: Select \'Regular Savings\' (Mandatory Contributions) from the menu',
      'Step 5: View your complete contribution history \u2014 it shows all contributions from your first remittance to the latest, including employee and employer shares',
      'Step 6: Check the total number of contributions, total employee share, total employer share, and accumulated dividends',
      'Step 7: Cross-reference with your payslips \u2014 every month your employer deducted Pag-IBIG should have a corresponding entry',
      'Step 8: If months are missing, contact your HR/payroll department immediately with your payslip evidence',
      'Step 9: To check MP2 savings (if enrolled): go back to the menu and select \'Modified Pag-IBIG II (MP2)\' to see your MP2 contributions and dividends',
      'Alternative: Download the Virtual Pag-IBIG Mobile App from Google Play or App Store for checking on the go',
    ],
    fees: 'Free \u2014 checking contributions online has no fees',
    processingTime: 'Instant \u2014 contribution records are available upon login. New contributions may take a few weeks to post after employer remittance',
    tips: [
      'Check your contributions at least quarterly to catch any non-remittance early',
      'Your total Pag-IBIG savings (employee + employer shares + dividends) can be withdrawn upon retirement, disability, or after 20 years of continuous membership',
      'You need 24 months of contributions to be eligible for Pag-IBIG housing loans and multi-purpose loans',
      'The annual dividend rate has been consistently between 5-7% \u2014 much higher than regular bank savings',
      'Consider enrolling in MP2 (Modified Pag-IBIG II) for voluntary savings that earn the same high dividend rate, tax-free',
      'If your employer is not remitting, report to the nearest Pag-IBIG branch \u2014 penalties apply to non-compliant employers',
      'You can also check your loan balance and loan payment history through Virtual Pag-IBIG',
      'Download statements periodically \u2014 they serve as proof of savings for loan applications',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Virtual Pag-IBIG Portal', url: 'https://www.pagibigfundservices.com/virtualpagibig/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Virtual Pag-IBIG Mobile App', url: 'https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=pagibigfund.virtualpagibigapp'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Pag-IBIG Fund Official Website', url: 'https://www.pagibigfund.gov.ph/'),
    ],
  ),
  '13th-month': ChecklistItem(
    id: '13th-month',
    title: 'Know your 13th month pay rights',
    description: 'All rank-and-file employees are legally entitled to 13th month pay \u2014 at least 1/12 of your basic annual salary, paid on or before December 24.',
    why: 'It\'s not a bonus \u2014 it\'s the law (Presidential Decree No. 851). Up to \u20B190,000 is tax-exempt. Some employers try to include it in monthly salary (\'already included\') which is illegal. Know your rights.',
    how: 'Formula: (Total Basic Salary Earned in a Year) \u00F7 12. Compute yours in Sandalan. If you think you were underpaid, file a complaint with DOLE (Department of Labor and Employment). Must be paid regardless of resignation or separation.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/thirteenth-month',
    appLinkLabel: '13th Month Calculator',
    requirements: [
      'Knowledge of your basic monthly salary (excluding overtime, holiday pay, night differential, and allowances unless stated in your contract)',
      'Your payslips for the year to verify total basic salary earned',
      'Employment contract (to check if additional pay components are included in basic salary computation)',
      'DOLE contact information in case of disputes',
    ],
    steps: [
      'Step 1: Understand the formula \u2014 13th Month Pay = Total Basic Salary Earned During the Year \u00F7 12',
      'Step 2: Identify your basic salary \u2014 this is your fixed monthly pay EXCLUDING overtime pay, holiday pay, night shift differential, and allowances (unless your contract says otherwise)',
      'Step 3: If you worked the full year (January-December) with a fixed salary, your 13th month pay equals one month\'s basic salary. Example: \u20B125,000/month x 12 months = \u20B1300,000 \u00F7 12 = \u20B125,000',
      'Step 4: If you worked only part of the year (prorated): multiply your monthly salary by the number of months worked, then divide by 12. Example: Started in July, \u20B125,000/month x 6 months = \u20B1150,000 \u00F7 12 = \u20B112,500',
      'Step 5: Check your payslip or ask HR when the 13th month pay will be released \u2014 it must be paid on or before December 24',
      'Step 6: Verify the amount received matches your computation. If it doesn\'t, request a breakdown from HR',
      'Step 7: If you believe you were underpaid or your employer refuses to pay, file a complaint with DOLE at the nearest regional office',
      'Step 8: Check the tax exemption \u2014 13th month pay and other benefits up to \u20B190,000 combined are tax-exempt. Amounts exceeding \u20B190,000 are subject to income tax',
    ],
    fees: 'N/A \u2014 13th month pay is an employee benefit, not a cost. It is required by law under Presidential Decree No. 851',
    processingTime: 'Must be paid by employer on or before December 24 of each year. Some employers pay half in June and the other half in December',
    tips: [
      '13th month pay is NOT a bonus \u2014 it\'s a mandatory benefit required by law. Your employer cannot skip it or \'include it\' in your monthly salary',
      'ALL rank-and-file employees are entitled to 13th month pay regardless of position, employment status (regular, probationary, contractual), or method of pay (daily, weekly, monthly)',
      'You are entitled to 13th month pay even if you resign or are terminated \u2014 it will be prorated based on months worked',
      'Overtime pay, holiday pay, night shift differential, and hazard pay are NOT included in the computation \u2014 only basic salary',
      'Some generous employers give 14th or 15th month pay as a Christmas bonus \u2014 this is voluntary and separate from the mandatory 13th month',
      'If your employer fails to pay by December 24, no exemption or deferment is allowed. Report non-compliance to DOLE',
      'Managers and supervisors are NOT entitled to 13th month pay under the law, but many companies extend it as a company benefit',
      'The \u20B190,000 tax exemption threshold covers 13th month pay PLUS all other benefits (Christmas bonus, productivity incentives, etc.) \u2014 only the excess is taxed',
    ],
    references: [
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DOLE 13th Month Pay Guidelines', url: 'https://laborlaw.ph/13th-month-pay/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'Presidential Decree No. 851', url: 'https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1975/12/16/presidential-decree-no-851-s-1975/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: 'DOLE Official Website', url: 'https://www.dole.gov.ph/'),
      ChecklistReference(label: '13th Month Pay Computation Guide', url: 'https://everythingatwork.com/how-to-compute-13th-month-pay-in-the-philippines-2025-update/'),
    ],
  ),

  // ─── Phase 4: Tax Compliance ────────────────────────────────────────────────
  'bir-2316': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'bir-2316',
    title: 'Get your BIR Form 2316 from your employer',
    description: 'Form 2316 is the Certificate of Compensation Payment and Tax Withheld \u2014 proof of your income and taxes paid, issued by your employer every January.',
    why: 'This document proves your tax was withheld correctly. You need it for loan applications (housing, bank), new employer onboarding, and to verify your annual tax was properly settled. Never lose it.',
    how: 'Ask HR or payroll every January for your 2316 covering the previous year. If your employer failed to issue one, they\'re violating the Tax Code. Scan it and keep a digital copy. Most employers issue it by January 31.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),
  'substituted-filing': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'substituted-filing',
    title: 'Know if you need to file an ITR yourself',
    description: 'Most pure employees with one employer qualify for Substituted Filing \u2014 meaning your employer files on your behalf and you don\'t need to file Form 1700.',
    why: 'Filing when not required wastes time. NOT filing when required leads to penalties of 25% surcharge + 12% interest per year + \u20B11,000 compromise penalty. Know your classification.',
    how: 'You don\'t need to file if: single employer, compensation income only, tax was correctly withheld, employer files BIR Alphalist. You MUST file (Form 1700) if: two or more employers in a year, business income, compensation exceeds \u20B12.4M, or you want a tax refund.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),
  'bir-freelancer': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'bir-freelancer',
    title: 'Register with BIR as freelancer or self-employed',
    description: 'If you have any income outside of a formal employer \u2014 freelancing, consulting, online selling, or a side business \u2014 you must register with BIR.',
    why: 'Unregistered businesses and freelancers face back taxes, 25% surcharge, 12% annual interest, and compromise penalties going back 3\u201310 years. The BIR has been actively running after digital earners and influencers.',
    how: 'File BIR Form 1901 at your RDO with TIN, proof of business address, and valid ID. Register your books of accounts. Print Official Receipts (ORs) or use the eBIRForms system. Annual registration fee: \u20B1500. File quarterly (1701Q) and annual (1701/1701A) ITR.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),
  'bir-deductions': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'bir-deductions',
    title: 'Know your allowable deductions',
    description: 'Self-employed individuals can deduct business expenses OR choose the Optional Standard Deduction (OSD) of 40% of gross income \u2014 whichever lowers your tax more.',
    why: 'Many self-employed Filipinos overpay because they don\'t know they can deduct internet, phone, home office, transportation, professional development, and health insurance premiums from their taxable income.',
    how: 'Keep receipts for all business-related expenses. If expenses exceed 40% of income, itemize. If not, use OSD. Also consider the 8% flat income tax option if gross sales/receipts are below \u20B13,000,000 \u2014 often simpler and lower than graduated rates.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/tools/taxes',
    appLinkLabel: 'BIR Tax Tracker',
  ),

  // ─── Phase 5: Insurance & Protection ────────────────────────────────────────
  'philhealth-benefits': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'philhealth-benefits',
    title: 'Learn how to actually use your PhilHealth',
    description: 'Knowing how to use your PhilHealth benefits can save you tens of thousands of pesos during hospitalization \u2014 most members don\'t claim what they\'re entitled to.',
    why: 'PhilHealth covers specific amounts per diagnosis (case rate) regardless of actual hospital bill. For normal delivery alone it covers \u20B16,500. Without knowing how to file, you leave money on the table.',
    how: 'Present PhilHealth ID + MDR at accredited hospital admission. The hospital files PhilHealth claims on your behalf. For outpatient: Z-benefits cover cancer, dialysis, and selected conditions. Check philhealth.gov.ph/services for the full benefits table.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
  ),
  'hmo': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'hmo',
    title: 'Get HMO coverage',
    description: 'An HMO (Health Maintenance Organization) covers outpatient consultations, diagnostics, and emergency room visits that PhilHealth doesn\'t fully cover.',
    why: 'PhilHealth mostly covers inpatient care. A single ER visit, lab workup, or specialist consultation can cost \u20B12,000\u2013\u20B110,000 out of pocket. HMO fills this gap. Company HMO is free \u2014 always enroll in it if offered.',
    how: 'If employed: enroll in your company\'s HMO during open enrollment \u2014 it\'s usually free or subsidized. If self-employed: personal plans from Maxicare, Medicard, or Intellicare start at ~\u20B13,000\u2013\u20B18,000/year. Compare online at HMO comparison sites.',
    priority: 'critical',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
  ),
  'life-insurance': ChecklistItem(
    id: 'life-insurance',
    title: 'Get term life insurance',
    description: 'Term life insurance pays your beneficiaries a lump sum if you die during the coverage period \u2014 pure protection with no investment component.',
    why: 'If anyone depends on your income (parents, spouse, kids), you need life insurance. Rule of thumb: 10x your annual income in coverage. Term insurance is 3\u20135x cheaper than VUL for the same coverage. Most Filipinos are oversold VULs when term would serve them better.',
    how: 'Get term insurance first: PRULife\'s PRUTerm One, Sun Life\'s SunTerm, or AXA\'s FlexiProtect. Annual premiums for \u20B11,000,000 coverage start around \u20B13,000\u2013\u20B15,000/year for a healthy 25-year-old. Avoid mixing insurance with investment (VUL) until you fully understand both.',
    priority: 'important',
    appLink: '/tools/insurance',
    appLinkLabel: 'Insurance Tracker',
  ),
  'ctpl': ChecklistItem(
